Thursday August 22nd 2013 3:24 pm -04:00,Ints & floats are different type of numbers.An int is an integer that means its a whole number with no decimal point so 12100-6 are all examples of integersA float is a number with a decimal point so 1.0 2.3 3.14159 -200.5 are all examples of floats.A string is a sequence of characters enclosed by quotes (either single or double quotes as long as the pair match)so Hello World Jack had 6 apples & Shes doing very well are all examples of strings.As Michael said there are far too many functions to memoize but with practice its like learning any language the ones you use frequently will become second nature and all the others can be looked up in the documentation., Resolved,2
Thursday August 22nd 2013 4:24 pm -04:00,Sounds like you have 2 different versions of Python installed Python2 & Python3 do integer arithmetic differently so in Python2 9/2 = 4 in Python3 9/2 = 4.5This is one of the significant differences between Python2 & Python3. In Python2 it says OK all of the values are integers so Im going to give you an integer result. If you say 9.0/2 in Python2 you should get 4.5 because one of the values is a float it gives you the answer as a float.In Python3 they changed it so that 9/2 will give the answer 4.5 if you still want to do integer arithmetic then you need to use the // operator so if you do 9//2 in Python3 the answer will be 4.Hope this helps =;-),None,0
