Friday August 23rd 2013 11:11 am -04:00,Here I knocked up a small example for you:def mymin(*args):                       # declare function with var # of args    curr_min = args[0]                  # set curr_min to first arg    for x in range(len(args)):          # for loop thru args tuple        if args[x] < curr_min:          # is this one less than curr_min?            curr_min = args[x]          # if so make current arg curr_min    return curr_min                     # return curr_minprint(str(mymin(624)))                # testprint(Expected 2)print(str(mymin(12345661245)))       # testprint(Expected 12)Of course for code youre going to rely on youd need to do things like check args didnt have zero length & things like that this is just a quick & dirty illustration of the idea. , Resolved,3
